collection begins with a lead essay by Khaled Abou El Fadl, who argues that democracy, especially a constitutional democracy that protects basic individual rights, is the form of government best suited to promoting a set of social and political values central to Islam. Because Islam is about submission to God and about each individual's responsibility to serve as His agent on Earth, Abou El Fadl argues, there is no place for the subjugation to human authority demanded by authoritarian regimes. The lead essay is followed by eleven others from internationally respected specialists in democracy and religion. They address, challenge, and engage Abou El Fadl's work. The contributors include John Esposito, Muhammad Fadel, Noah Feldman, Nader Hashemi, Bernard Haykel, Muqtedar Khan, Saba Mahmood, David Novak, William Quandt, Kevin Reinhart, and Jeremy Waldron.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aDemocracyxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aIslam and politicszIslamic countries. 0aIslam and politics. 0aIslamy21st century. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Law.2bisacsh1 aChasman, Deborah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCohen, Joshua, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEsposito, John L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFadel, Mohammad H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeldman, Noah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHashemi, Nader A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaykel, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhan, M. A. Muqtedar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMahmood, Saba, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNovak, David, econtribu